@node editorial "Editorial"

@{FG Shine}Welcome to AmiChannel News@{FG Text}

Hello and welcome to the 1 issue of @{B}AmiChannel News@{UB}.

I must confess that this is the second time I write an editorial for a magazine.
The  first time was with the first issue of the e-magazine you are reading. That
editorial  was very easy to write because it was only the presentation. But now,
it  is different. A lot of things has happened in this month. Probably, you have
read  already  tons  of  articles  about the big news. Some positives, some very
negatives.  In  case you miss the whole story, don't worry. You will found it in
this issue. Anyway I highly recommend you to read the @{" report " Link woa39} by @{I}B. Hutchings @{UI}
(the best report  I read in years) and the @{" FAQ " Link woa40} which recently appeared in the
@{B}Amiga Inc.@{UB} web site.

Some  friends  of  mine have asked me my opinion. It's not so easy. Of course, I
would  like  to  @{I}`see  the @{B}Amiga @{UB}blow the socks off everything else that is out @{UI}
@{I}there', @{UI} as  @{I}Carl  Sassenrath @{UI}exclaimed in a demonstration of the predecessor to
the   so called @{B}MMC@{UB}. But, @{B}Amiga Inc.@{UB} has made two big mistakes: the first one is
rel ated  with  the  way  of doing things, and the other one is related with the
support of current machines. 

The  press  release "Kick-off the future with @{B}Amiga@{UB}" is a perfect example of how
not  to write a press release. Instead of clarify things, it confused everybody.
Fortunately,  they  are solving this mistake releasing little notes explaining a
bit better what the future plans are.

As  you  probably know, the current machines will not be supported by the mother
company.  And  this is the key point, the mother of all the controversies. As at
the  moment  of  the  conference this point had not been solved, a lot of people
thought  that @{B}Amiga Inc.@{UB} was abandoning the @{B}Amiga@{UB}. And this is not the case. The
now  called  @{B}Amiga Classic@{UB} will be supported by @{B}Phase 5@{UB} and @{B}Haage & Partner@{UB}, two
german companies that finally solved their problems about the @{B}PowerPC@{UB} standard.

Sadly,  in  this  month  of  May,  we  have  seen how @{B}Oregon Research@{UB} was out of
business,  @{B}Deimos Desing@{UB} has abandoned the Amiga scene, and the @{B}Amiga Games@{UB} page
(kept by @{I}Eddie Ivanov @{UI}) has been closed.

Apart from the @{B}WOA@{UB} mess, you will find in this issue two articles which has been
written  by @{I}Miguel Ramos, @{UI}one of the most active person of the spanish scene. In
one  of  them, he explains the hard situation of the @{B}Amiga@{UB} in Spain. I asked him
to  write  this  article  because  it  seems  that  all  the @{B}Amiga@{UB} companies and
celebrities think that there is not market outside UK, Germany and USA. And this
is  unfair.  If  the  spanish @{B}Amiga@{UB} community had more support from outsied, the
number of spanish @{B}Amiga@{UB}s would be increased for sure.

Anyway,  to  show our support and entusiasm, we have a lot of surprises for you.
However,  I  have signed a NDA as many others ;-), so I can't tell you anything.
But, I can tell you that we have BIG news. So, stay tuned!

Remember to visit the SAU website, which is located in:

	@{B}http://www.arrakis.es/amiga/@{UB}                (Spain)

or you can visit any of its mirrors:

	@{B}http://club.idecnet.com/~dragon/sau/@{UB}        (Spain)
	@{B}http://soporte.databasedm.es/amiga/sau/@{UB}     (Spain)
	@{B}http://www.isocanda.org/per/sau/@{UB}            (Academic Net)
	@{B}http://www.larevisteria.com/sau/@{UB}            (California, USA)

And if you want to contribute to this effort, you can send your articles to:

	@{I}sau@isocanda.org @{UI}

Thanks for reading and I hope you enjoy this issue.

===============================================================================
