@node not6 "DEIMOS DESIGN CANCELS PPC SUPPORT"

@{FG Shine}DEIMOS DESIGN CANCELS PPC SUPPORT@{FG Text}

@{FG Fill}DATE: 1998/05/12@{FG Text}

@{I}Press Release@{UI}

@{B}Deimos  Design@{UB},  the team behind @{B}Maim & Mangle@{UB} has decided to cancel any and all
@{B}PPC@{UB}  support  in  it's  forth  coming title, @{B}Maim & Mangle@{UB}. This was not an easy
decision  to  reach,  however,  we  feel  this is the only ethical way for us to
continue development.

This  decision  came  as a result of many factors, and we would like to take the
rest  of  this  announcement  to  address these points. For the record, we fully
believe  that any hope the @{B}Amiga@{UB} platform has of a future is with open, industry
standard  hardware,  and  an  updated  @{B}OS@{UB}.  However, we do not believe that this
future lays with the @{B}PowerUp@{UB} boards.

@{I}Cost Of The @{B}PowerUp @{UB}Investment @{UI}

An  overwhelming factor is cost. The big-boxed @{B}PowerUp@{UB} boards (the @{B}CS-PPC@{UB} range,
with  a  50Mhz  @{B}060@{UB}, a 233Mhz @{B}604e@{UB}, and no RAM) costs just under $2000 CAD after
taxes.  No  other  solutions  exist.  For  that  price, one could buy a complete
@{B}Pentium  II@{UB}  system. For the few benefits you get, we cannot justify the cost to
ourselves (try as we might).

That  is an economic reality that a lot of people (including some of us) will no
longer  ignore. Hence, not all of us will be buying @{B}PowerUp@{UB} cards, now or in the
future.  Now,  if we will not purchase these cards, it is simply hypocritical of
us to ask fellow @{B}Amiga@{UB} users to do so. We will not do that.

@{I}Lifespan of the Hardware @{UI}

We  also  believe that the @{B}PowerUp@{UB} boards are a short term stepping stone / hold
over.  There  is  no  guarantee  that  a  future @{B}AmigaOS@{UB} will ever support these
boards,  and  therefore,  they  potentially  have  even less value. Until the OS
supports the HW, any and all future HW developments are one big bandage. It does
nothing to heal the sickness, it only prolongs the suffering.

@{I}Which System To Use? @{UI}

Our  first  priority upon obtaining the @{B}PowerUp@{UB} hardware was to evaluate each SW
system  for  ourselves,  by ourselves. We ignored the statements from both sides
(as  each  side  is  obviously  biased  towards  their  system)  and  decided to
investigate them independently.

Suffice  to  say, that from our own analysis we decided that @{B}WarpUp@{UB} was the best
solution for @{B}Maim & Mangle@{UB}. It clearly won us over on many factors:

 * Documentation.
 * Installation and ease of use.
 * @{B}PPC@{UB} native graphics support (RTG Master).
 * Stable development system, which worked as documented.
 * Shared Libraries *now* - a large part of our shared code.

We  then  decided  that  since our game would be supporting @{B}PPC@{UB} hardware, @{B}Phase5@{UB}
would  understand  our  decision (even if they did not like it) as it would only
mean more sales for them.

We  could  not be further from the truth! Basically, we were expected to support
@{B}PowerUp@{UB},  no  matter  what  the cost. Our viewpoint was that our usage of @{B}WarpUp@{UB}
meant:

 * It was still support for their fledging hardware.
 * It would mean more sales for them (regardless of the software used).
 * Using @{B}PowerUp@{UB} would adversely impact our development schedule.
 * Using  @{B}PowerUp@{UB}  would  effect  the @{B}PPC@{UB} support of the title (as less code was
   appropriate for the @{B}PPC@{UB} side under @{B}PowerUp@{UB} (the graphics system being a major
   consideration for this game).
 * It would effect the overall quality of the title.

Despite  the  fact  that is was still support for their product, it was not good
enough. It was basically all or nothing.

We  then  decided  to  go  back and re-evaluate @{B}PowerUp@{UB}, with the potential side
effect of scraping several months of work. Needless to say, we were not pleased.

@{I}Ulterior Motives? @{UI}

As  @{B}Phase5@{UB}  are first and foremost an add-on hardware company, one has to wonder
why  they  are  so  forceful  about using only the @{B}PowerUp@{UB} system. After all, no
matter  what software is used, it is only more sales for them (they are the only
provider of @{B}Amiga PPC@{UB} hardware).

It  does not tax their support department, they have stated that @{B}WarpUp@{UB} is not a
supported  system  (obviously  this job falls to @{B}H&P@{UB}). It does not hamper future
developments,  @{B}WarpUp@{UB}  would  have to adapt to future hardware developments, not
the reverse. What then, is the problem?

In @{B}Deimos Designs@{UB} opinion, it comes down to the fact that @{B}Phase5@{UB}'s objectives do
not coincide with the @{B}Amiga@{UB}s future. @{B}Phase5@{UB} have publicly stated that @{B}PowerUp@{UB} is
a  migration  path  to  a "real @{B}PPC OS@{UB}", with the side effect of speeding up the
current host system (i.e. your @{B}Amiga@{UB}). This has been stated in public forums and
on  the @{B}Phase5@{UB} website (@{B}http://www.phase5.de@{UB}). It has also been stated that this
"real  @{B}PPC  OS@{UB}"  is  not the proposed @{B}Amiga OS 4.0@{UB}. This can only mean that this
"real @{B}PPC OS@{UB}" is the planned @{B}A\Box OS@{UB}, not a future revision of the @{B}Amiga OS@{UB}.

That  is  fair  enough  -  they  are  free to do whatever they please with their
company  and  products.  However,  @{B}Deimos  Design@{UB}  does  not consider such plans
helpful  to  the  @{B}Amiga@{UB}s  future and therefore we will not support their efforts
with our software.

@{I}Why Not @{B}WarpUp @{UB}? @{UI}

At this point, you may ask @{I}"Well then why not use @{B}WarpUp @{UB}?" @{UI}That is a very valid
point,  and  one which we considered. @{B}Deimos Design@{UB} had planned to go ahead with
@{B}WarpUp@{UB} until recent activities came to light.

The  final  straw came when @{B}Phase5@{UB} elected to put the @{B}PowerUp@{UB} system software in
the  flash-ROM.  We simply disagree with the practice of starting *any* software
system from third party hardware.

The  purpose of an expansion card ROM is to configure the card for OS usage, not
to  start  up  a  dedicated OS extension. Despite asking @{B}Phase5@{UB} some valid, open
questions, they chose to simply ignore us, rather than provide a valid technical
justification.

You  might  now  say,  @{I}"Well  @{B}WarpUp @{UB} will  find  a way to disable the @{B}PowerUp @{UB}
software". @{UI} Very  true,  there will always be a way around the @{B}PowerUp@{UB} software,
eventually.  That  is the key word, @{I}"eventually" @{UI}. @{B}Phase5@{UB} are free to change the
manor  in  which  the  @{B}PowerUp@{UB}  SW  is started with each and every update of the
flash-ROM.  This  means that @{B}WarpUp@{UB} could conceivably be disabled for weeks at a
time,  with  each  and  every  flash-ROM  update.  While @{B}WarpUp@{UB} would eventually
circumvent  this,  it would have a very negative effect on any products based on
@{B}WarpUp@{UB}. In @{B}Deimos Design@{UB}'s opinion, this is the desired effect.

@{I}Effects On @{B}Maim & Mangle @{UB}and @{B}The World Foundry @{UB}@{UI}

The  main  concern  is  -  what  are  the effects on @{B}Maim & Mangle@{UB} and @{B}The World
Foundry@{UB}?

The  first  concern  is  @{B}Maim & Mangle@{UB}. Unfortunately, some of the features will
obviously  have  to  be  scaled  back,  or  be removed completely. As far as the
overall  impact  on  @{B}Maim & Mangle@{UB}, this is still under evaluation. When we have
completed our evaluation, we will announce the results.

The  second  part is, how does this effect @{B}The World Foundry@{UB}? Unfortunately, TWF
is   also  drastically  affected.  @{B}The  World  Foundry@{UB} was  first  and  foremost
established  to  create  and promote utilisation of high end equipment by games.
Obviously,  @{B}Deimos  Designs@{UB}  decision  to  cancel  @{B}PPC@{UB} support has a fundamental
conflict with that goal.

Therefore,  @{B}Deimos  Design@{UB}  has  withdrawn  from  @{B}The  World  Foundry@{UB}, effective
immediately.  We  would  like  to  assure  everyone  that we still have a strong
relationship  with  our  former partners, however, we feel it would be unfair to
them to remain a part of @{B}TWF@{UB}.

To  remove  any  and  all  doubt, we would like to state (on behalf of @{B}TWF@{UB}) that
@{B}Explorer  2260 PPC@{UB} is still being actively developed. This announcement does not
effect  @{B}Explorer  2260@{UB},  or the remaining members of @{B}TWF@{UB}, only @{B}Deimos Design@{UB} and
@{B}M&M@{UB}.

@{I}Conclusion @{UI}

In  conclusion,  the @{B}Deimos Design@{UB} team has currently decided to revert to a @{B}68K@{UB}
only  development  plan.  We  will not support attempts to migrate the remaining
market  to  an  alternate platform. The market needs to unite instead of bicker,
now more than ever.

If the @{B}Amiga@{UB} ever sees a native @{B}PPC OS@{UB}, we will of course consider supporting it
with  @{B}PPC@{UB}  native games. However, at this point we will bow out of the @{B}Amiga PPC@{UB}
market.

We  realise  that  this will not be a popular decision, and that not many people
will agree with it. That is, of course, your right. No matter how unpopular this
will make us, we stand by our decision and will not support a company that tries
to  artificially  limit  the end users choices. It is your right to run whatever
software  you  want  on  hardware  you  have  purchased, not a privilege which a
company can revoke at will.

Any  questions  or  comments  should be directed to @{B}Deimos Design@{UB}, not @{B}The World
Foundry@{UB}

