@node not12 "MIAMI 3.0 IS NOW AVALAIBLE FROM SCHATZTRUHE"

@{FG Shine}MIAMI 3.0 IS NOW AVALAIBLE FROM SCHATZTRUHE@{FG Text}

@{FG Fill}DATE: 1998/05/12@{FG Text}

@{B}MIAMI 3.0@{UB} is now available from Schatztruhe!

Suggested Retail Price DM 79.00

US$1.00 = DM 1,77 given today's exchange rates!

Ordering  information:  The most convenient method of placing an order is to use
our  electronic  order form located at @{B}http://www.schatztruhe.de/order.html@{UB}. You
can also send an E-Mail to @{I}stefano@schatztruhe.de @{UI}including your address and the
products you wish to order.

@{B}Miami  3.0@{UB}  is  a  TCP/IP  protocol stack to access the Internet by modem, cable
modem,  ISDN  modem,  or to access local networks by Ethernet/Arcnet. We deliver
@{B}Miami 3.0@{UB} on three floppy-discs together with the license-code.

@{B}Miami 3.0@{UB} features

 * Replaces   @{B}AmiTCP/IP@{UB}  (@{B}bsdsocket.library@{UB})  in  an  API-compatible  way,  i.e.
   standard  clients  and  servers  for  @{B}AmiTCP/IP@{UB} usually also work with @{B}Miami@{UB}.
   Clients  for  @{B}I-Net  225@{UB}  or @{B}AS-225@{UB} can also be used with @{B}Miami@{UB}, using the PD
   @{B}socket.library@{UB} emulation library from @{UB}Aminet@{UB}.
 * Contains  a  complete TCP/IP protocol stack for point-to-point connections to
   your  Internet  provider  allowing  you  to  access the Internet, and for LAN
   (Ethernet/Arcnet) access.
 * Is  based  on the latest BSD TCP/IP code (Net/3 as distributed in 4.4BSD/Lite
   version 2), augmented by @{B}FreeBSD 2.x@{UB} extensions.
 * Supports RFC-1323 extensions for higher performance TCP.
 * Is a "true" TCP/IP implementation, not a "hack" that requires a shell account
   with additional programs running at your Internet provider.
 * @{B}Miami@{UB}  does  support the TCP/IP emulators @{B}"Slirp"@{UB} (by @{I}Danny Gasparovski @{UI}) and
   TIA though, so @{B}Miami@{UB} can also be used together with shell accounts.
 * Supports  SLIP,  CSLIP  and  PPP  as  built-in protocols without the need for
   SANA-II  drivers. The PPP implementation is rather fast and comprehensive and
   supports, for example, PAP, CHAP, authentication protocol fallback for @{B}Win-NT@{UB}
   servers,  and  VJC  TCP  header  compression.  The  PPP  code is based on the
   thoroughly  tested  code of ppp.device, but all PPP parameters are configured
   automatically by @{B}Miami@{UB}.
 * Also  supports  most  SANA-II  device drivers (for Ethernet, Arcnet and other
   network hardware).
 * Has  an  integrated  graphical user interface (based on @{B}MUI 3.3@{UB}, copyright by
   @{I}Stefan  Stuntz, @{UI} or  @{B}GTLayout@{UB},  by @{I}Olaf Barthel @{UI}) for *all* configuration and
   runtime  parameters,  including  the  settings  for  TCP/IP, interfaces, PPP,
   protocols,  dialing,  inetd, user database etc. The user interface module can
   be unloaded at any time to save memory.
 * Does not require the installation or modification of any external text files,
   libraries,  devices, environment variables, tool types etc. The configuration
   is  done  completely through the graphical user interface, and all parameters
   are  stored  in  a  single @{B}IFF@{UB} settings file. Functions to import/export many
   settings  from/to  @{B}ASCII@{UB}  text  files  (as  used  e.g.  by  @{B}Unix@{UB}  hosts or by
   @{B}AmiTCP/IP@{UB}) are available, too.
 * Has  a  built-in script-driven dialer with support for multiple phone numbers
   and  optional interactive mode. In the demo version up to 3 phone numbers are
   supported. In the registered version there is no limit.
 * Supports auto-redialing on several phone numbers during dialing.
 * Supports static and dynamic IP addresses for SLIP, CSLIP and PPP.
 * Supports  DHCP  and  BootP, and has an automatic dial log analyzer to support
   dynamic IP addresses even with SLIP and CSLIP.
 * Supports teach-in dialing, i.e. in most cases you do not even have to write a
   dial  script,  but  only  need  to  connect to your provider once manually in
   interactive  mode,  and  @{B}Miami@{UB}  will  "learn"  how to automatically log in by
   itself the next time you want to connect, i.e. @{B}Miami@{UB} will generate a suitable
   dial script by itself.
 * Supports  Arcnet  according  to  the  old  (RFC 826/1051) standard as well as
   according  to  the  new (RFC 1201) standard, for compatibility with Linux and
   Win95/NT.
 * Has extensive security features, including ping flood protection, IP fragment
   protection,    configurable    SYN  flood  protection,  IP  address  spoofing
   protection,  protection  from  "land",  plus  additional  packet  filter  and
   monitoring functions.
 * Has  many  of  the  popular  demons  (TCP/UDP servers) already built in, e.g.
   inetd, identd and fingerd.
 * Has  a  configurable,  dynamic  hostname  cache  to  reduce the number of DNS
   lookups  and  thus  speed  up  TCP  connection  setup, in particular with WWW
   browsers.
 * Allows  you  to  reconnect after a reset (without dialing) even with Internet
   providers that usually do not support this.
 * Is  completely  localized. (English/German at this time. Many other languages
   are in preparation).
 * Supports several new @{B}MUI 3.x@{UB} features (such as "drag&drop", "bubble help" and
   "context  menus")  as  well  as extensive context-sensitive online help, when
   using the @{B}MUI@{UB} interface module.
 * Support PPP-Callback/Dialback in a way that is compatible to Win-NT.
 * Supports SOCKS V4/V5 proxy servers to bypass firewalls.
 * Implements SANA-II R3, for better throughput with new SANA-II devices.
 * Supports  multicasting  level-2 and multicast routing for MBone compatibility
   and support of live audio/video applications.
 * Supports  automatic  redial/reconnect  on  hangup  (works best with static IP
   addresses),  and  automatic  execution  of  @{B}ARexx@{UB} scripts when certain events
   occur (start, end, online, offline etc.).
 * Phone bill data can be exported to a text file.
 * Supports  T/TCP  (TCP for transaction) for faster web browsing; supports Path
   MTU discovery for better performance across Ethernet and BSD packet filter.
 * Has a built-in IP filter to restrict and monitor access to your machine.
 * Comes  with  @{B}MiamiRemind@{UB},  a tool that can automatically hang up the line for
   you  after  a  period  of  inactivity, to save on phone costs. @{B}MiamiRemind@{UB} is
   highly configurable.
 * Comes  with  an additional configuration utility @{B}MiamiInit@{UB} that allows you to
   get  connected  to the Internet without configuring @{B}Miami@{UB} first. All you need
   to  do is answer a few questions with information your Internet provider gave
   you. @{B}MiamiInit@{UB} then dials up your Internet connection, verifies your data and
   tries to find out all remaining configuration parameters by itself. @{B}MiamiInit@{UB}
   will  only  ask  additional  questions  if  it  was  unable to determine some
   required  parameters by itself. Extensive online help is available throughout
   this  process.  @{B}MiamiInit@{UB},  like  @{B}Miami@{UB},  is  completely  localized and has a
   graphical  user  interface using @{B}MUI 3.3@{UB} or @{B}GTLayout@{UB}. @{B}MiamiInit@{UB} also supports
   cable   modems,   ADSL,  local  Ethernet  networks,  Magplip  and  may  other
   configurations. @{B}MiamiInit@{UB} contains extensive database of modems, ISDN TAs and
   ISDN  boards  for  automatic  configuration  of  init  strings, ISDN protocol
   conversion etc.
 * Comes  with  a  large  set  of  Internet tools: @{B}MiamiFinger@{UB}, @{B}MiamiTraceRoute@{UB},
   @{B}Miami! Ping@{UB} and many others.

