@node woa40 "THE BIG ANNOUNCEMENTS BY BEN HUTCHINGS"

@{FG Shine}THE BIG ANNOUNCEMENTS BY BEN HUTCHINGS@{FG Text}

@{FG Fill}DATE: 1998/05/19@{FG Text}

From: @{I}Ben Hutchings <worc0223@sable.ox.ac.uk> @{UI}
Newsgroups: comp.sys.amiga.misc
Subject: The big announcements
Followup-To: poster
Date: 18 May 1998 21:45:08 +0100
Organization: Oxford University
Sender: @{I}womble@eldritch.dyn.ml.org @{UI}

Here's  my  (rather hurried) report on Friday's announcements. It's based on the
notes  I  made  at  the  time,  plus  additional details I remembered, plus some
clarifications  I got later from @{I}Fleecy Moss @{UI}and @{I}Joe Torre. @{UI}It could probably be
improved quite a bit, but I haven't got time to do that right now.

If  you  need to reply to me, please use e-mail, as I am unsubscribing from this
group until my final university exams are over (late June).

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

The  presentation  took  place in a large hall on the first and second floors of
Novotel. @{I}Petro Tyschtschenko @{UI}was first to speak; he began by presenting gifts to
the  @{B}World  of  Amiga@{UB}  organisers  (@{I}Peter  Brameld @{UI} and @{I}Norah Hodgson @{UI}). Then he
summarised  what @{B}Amiga International@{UB} had been doing in the past year, mentioning
shows,  the  website,  new  licenses,  the success of @{B}Amigas@{UB} in the Indian video
market, and continuing sales of @{B}Amigas@{UB} for kiosk systems.

@{I}Jeff Schindler @{UI}then stepped up to make the announcements we were all waiting for
(well, except those journalists who had been to the lunchtime event). He thanked
@{I}Petro, @{UI} and  then  introduced  the  @{B}Amiga  Inc@{UB} employees present. @{I}Marilyn Flint @{UI}
(Manager), @{I}Joe Torre @{UI}(Hardware Engineer), and @{I}Darreck Lisle @{UI}(Events Coordinator)
were  all  there.  @{B}Gateway@{UB} was represented by @{I}Jim Collas, @{UI}Senior Vice President,
and  @{I}Steve  Johns, @{UI} Head of Corporate Development. @{I}Jeff @{UI}then announced three new
employees - @{I}Fleecy Moss @{UI}(Project Manager), @{I}Dr Allan Havemose @{UI}(Head of Technology
and Development), and @{I}Bill McEwen @{UI}(PR).

The  business plan that has now been approved for funding by @{B}Gateway@{UB} is the 15th
in  a  series  of  refinements  by  @{I}Jeff. @{UI} Unfortunately  not all of it could be
revealed  as some details (about a third of the information that was intended to
be announced) have yet to be agreed with outside companies. The rest is expected
to be finalised within about a month.

@{I}Jeff  Schindler @{UI} showed a series of slides (using @{B}Powerpoint@{UB}, sadly) summarising
his  points.  I noted down much of the content of these so I could remember what
was  said.  The  key  question  for @{B}Amiga@{UB} is, how can it regain a lead? The next
question  that  can be asked is, what defines an @{B}Amiga@{UB}? @{B}Amiga Inc@{UB} decided it was
not  specific  technologies,  but  the  vision:  awesome  technology, freedom of
choice,  an enthusiast following, a worldwide community, and so on. So the goals
for   future   @{B}Amiga@{UB}   technology   are   these:  ease  of  use,  affordability,
high-performance  multimedia,  an  open  architecture,  evolution  to  meet  new
standards, and of course fun.

What is the market that @{B}Amiga@{UB} can attack now? @{B}Amiga Inc@{UB} identified the so-called
"digital  convergence"  market.  This  is the fusion of Internet access, digital
media  and  entertainment,  with  real  computers  underneath,  of course. It is
predicted  that there will soon be an electronic paradigm shift, with ubiquitous
digital  appliances.  Among  products  that might run @{B}AmigaOS@{UB} in the future are:
Internet  appliances,  games  machines  with  Internet  and DVD support, set-top
boxes,  sub-$500  computers,  combined  TV/game/computers  for  the  bedroom  or
kitchen,  @{B}PC@{UB}/TVs,  and  of  course  the conventional tower, desktop and portable
computers.

To  do  this,  @{B}AmigaOS@{UB}  needs  to  run  on  cheap,  fast hardware. @{B}Amiga Inc@{UB} has
discovered,  through @{B}Gateway@{UB}'s connections, a chip in development that can offer
incredible speed at a low price starting from next year. (It's being kept secret
by  the  company  developing  it  -  apparently, partly for fear of losing their
current  good  relations  with  @{B}Intel@{UB}  before the chip is in production.) Quoted
performance  statistics  were:  5-10  times  faster  than  current  high-end  @{B}PC@{UB}
hardware,  400  million  pixels  per second 3D rendering (in 24 bit colour, with
whatever 3D effects you want), and decoding of 4 MPEG2 streams at the same time.
It  can also support high-speed Internet access using ADSL or similar protocols.
Of  course hardware isn't everything. @{B}Amiga Inc@{UB} will need to provide breakway OS
technology - "convergence-ware" that will be perfectly suited to the sort of new
products that were mentioned above. This will mean a new OS core and new APIs.

The  next  slide  showed  how  @{I}Carl  Sassenrath @{UI} had reacted to the news. He was
present  at  a  demonstration  of the predecessor to this chip, along with @{B}Amiga
Inc@{UB}, and reportedly said: @{I}`It will be fun to again see the @{UB}Amiga @{UB}"blow the socks
off"  everything  else  that is out there.' @{UI}He said that @{B}REBOL Technologies@{UB} will
support the new @{B}AmigaOS@{UB}, which might interest you...

Now  comes the controversial bit. There is a long way from the current (1992/93)
@{B}Amiga   OS@{UB}   and  hardware  to  this  new  cutting-edge  chip  and  an  OS  with
"convergence-ware",  and that jump needs to be made in 18 months. The plan is to
do this in two steps. Current technology - @{B}AGA@{UB}, @{B}OS 3.1@{UB}, and @{B}680x0@{UB} - is described
as  @{B}"Amiga  Classic"@{UB}.  The  first  step from this will be to the @{B}"Amiga Bridge"@{UB},
which will consist of an @{B}x86 PC@{UB} running @{B}OS 4.0@{UB}, with an optional @{B}"Amiga Classic"@{UB}
bridge card. This will be the development platform for the next step. The use of
the  bridge  card  means that it can also run existing programs very fast, so it
may  well  be useful to non-developers too. The second step is to @{B}OS 5.0@{UB} running
on  a  new  architecture  in "digital convergence" products (which still include
conventional  computers). This will be basically software-compatible to the last
@{B}4.x@{UB} release.

What  are  the  building  blocks  for these two steps? Backward compatibility is
provided  by  the  bridge  card  (based on the @{B}Siamese@{UB} or @{B}InsideOut PCI@{UB} cards in
development)  or  by  @{B}UAE@{UB} (which should run just fine on the new chip!). For the
development platform, an OS kernel will be licensed from another company to save
time. The choice of kernel is yet to be announced. All along the way, there will
be  software  upgrades  to  meet  future  standards.  The  backing  of the Amiga
developer community is an essential.

The software timetable is as follows:
Developer program begins   Q3 of 1998
@{B}OS 4.0@{UB} release          November 1998
@{B}OS 5.0@{UB} ready                late 1999

The  developer  program will be handled by @{B}ICOA@{UB} together with @{B}Amiga Inc.@{UB} It will
provide support for porting applications and creating native applications for @{B}OS
4/5@{UB}.  Developers  will also be involved in the process of designing APIs for the
new  platform.  Developer kits and complete systems (@{B}PC@{UB} + bridge card + OS) will
be  available  from  @{B}Amiga Inc@{UB}. There was a meeting on Saturday morning where an
outline  of  OS  plans was presented, but for the time being that information is
not public.

Key  targets  for  @{B}OS  4.x@{UB}  will  be:  @{B}OS 3.1@{UB} compatibility; advanced multimedia
performance;  support  for open standards (such as @{B}OpenGL@{UB}); real-time, threaded,
protected,  pre-emptive  multi-tasking;  a  new  GUI;  full  Internet support. I
believe  the planned features for @{B}OS 3.5@{UB} will be included in @{B}4.x@{UB}. @{B}OS 5.0@{UB} will be
the  final  result  of all the additions made to @{B}OS 4.0,@{UB} but will run on the new
chip instead of on @{B}x86 PCs@{UB}.

There  was  brief  mention of the importance of user groups and the existence of
the  @{B}UGN@{UB} as an interface to @{B}Amiga Inc@{UB} - though not an exclusive one. There was a
@{B}UGN@{UB}  meeting  on  Sunday  morning,  but I didn't go to that. @{I}Jeff @{UI}also sought to
reassure  @{B}Amiga@{UB}  distributors that there was still plenty of opportunity to sell
"legacy"  software  and hardware, because new developments will retain backwards
compatibility. The possibilities for new products are of course greater.

Next to speak was @{I}Dr Allan Havemose, @{UI}the new Head of Technology and Development.
He has previously worked for @{B}Commodore-Amiga@{UB}, building up the European developer
network, and leading the OS development team for releases @{B}2.1@{UB}-@{B}3.1@{UB}. He didn't add
much  to  what @{I}Jeff Schindler @{UI}had said, and unfortunately I didn't take notes of
what he did say!

Some  more  details  that  came  out  in  response  to  questions. (These aren't
verbatim, but a combination of my notes and memory.)

Q. @{I}Why aren't you supporting the @{B}PPC @{UB}as a development platform? @{UI}
A. We're  negotiating with @{B}P5@{UB} for support for the @{B}PPC@{UB}. There should be news in a
   month.

Q. @{I}How do you plan to get a new kernel etc all in place by November? @{UI}
A. We're  teaming up with another OS corporation to use their kernel. @{B}BeOS@{UB}, @{B}Java
   OS@{UB}, @{B}Linux@{UB} and others are under consideration.

(Note, this is just for @{B}OS 4.0@{UB}.)

Q. @{I}What happened to @{B}OS 3.5 @{UB}? @{UI}
A. @{B}OS  3.5@{UB}  has been dropped. We looked at the plans and realised it wouldn't be
   worth doing, when we need to get @{B}OS 4.0@{UB} done by November.

Q. @{I}How can a little company like @{B}Amiga Inc @{UB}get access to this mystery chip? And @{UI}
   @{I}who is making it? @{B}Intel @{UB}? @{UI}
A. @{B}Gateway@{UB}  and its business partners are negotiating for the rights to use this
   chip. We can't say who is making it, but it's not @{B}Intel@{UB}.

Q. @{I}What will @{B}Amiga Inc @{UB}do to get @{B}PC @{UB}software companies to port to the @{B}Amiga @{UB}? @{UI}
A. We  can  use @{B}Gateway@{UB}'s contacts to try to persuade them to allow these ports,
   and we will support @{B}Amiga@{B} developers who want to work on them.

Q. @{I}Who's making the bridge card, and what processor will be on it? @{UI}
A. @{I}Mick Tinker @{UI}and @{I}Steve Jones @{UI}are working on it. It can use a @{B}68040@{UB} or @{B}68060@{UB}.

-- 
