@node art1 "AMIGA SITUATION IN SPAIN"

@{FG Shine}AMIGA SITUATION IN SPAIN@{FG Text}

Many  people from outside Spain think that there are no @{B}Amiga@{UB} users still active
in Spain, but the truth is approximately here:

As  other countries, been an @{B}Amiga@{UB} user today is very difficult, all of you know
how difficult is to get a decent soft/hard support in your local area, is almost
impossible,  you  have  to  use  mail  order  due  the  few  places to get @{B}Amiga@{UB}
hard/soft,  and  newcomers  to  the  machine or people interested on it, have to
leave  it  due  the lack of publicity and information on their city, and is even
worse  in  Spain,  where  the  official support of the @{B}Amiga@{UB} is NIL, the Spanish
market  now is better than some years ago, but it need a lot of help to start to
go up.

Only  a  few shops exist in Spain, but they are very dedicated and even some can
be  @{B}Amiga@{UB}-only  shops, so the market is still viable here, but the big expansion
of  clonics, the little information about the @{B}Amiga@{UB} and the old @{B}Amiga@{UB} equipment,
the market is not as big as it should.

Some years ago, the Spanish version of @{B}Amiga World@{UB} was on almost every kiosk but
since  the  @{B}Commodore@{UB}  fall,  the magazine had to close, leaving a whole country
without @{B}Amiga@{UB} information in Spanish.

Then  a new magazine was born, it was made by @{B}Amiga@{UB} users who loved the machine,
the  mag lasts some years informing and giving hopes to all the @{B}Amiga@{UB} users lost
in Spain, users who do not know any @{B}Amigans@{UB} in their cities.

But  now,  one year ago, the latest printed @{B}Amiga@{UB} magazine closed, so many users
had  to  sell theirs machine because the magazine was their only connection with
the @{B}Amiga@{UB} Community, mainly users that do not have Internet.

The  magazine  did  not have too much to do compared to other magazines from UK,
but some issues were great, even one had a Cover-CD!

The  latest issues of the magazine, were very poor, the editors were planning to
abandon  the  @{B}Amiga@{UB} market so the collaborators had to do almost the whole work,
well, the magazine was getting thinner every month and so on.

Finally, the magazine officially was 'frozen' but in my opinion, it was dead and
buried... It was a shame, It did a social function.

Another  great  focus on @{B}Amiga@{UB} information is an @{B}Amiga@{UB} section named @{I}AmigaMania @{UI}
in  a consoles-only-magazine which takes over 4 pages! mainly covering games and
answering questions to readers interested on the @{B}Amiga@{UB}!

Also  the  same  person who writes that section, whose name is @{I}Raul Monton@{UI} , aka
@{I}The Punisher@{UI}, writes in a national newspaper computer's supplement another @{B}Amiga@{UB}
section, in this case, covering news and events!

An excellent Work!

But  in  Spain there are some 'electronic' magazines, the pioneer was @{B}Fanzine@{UB} an
e-zine  covering  @{B}Amiga@{UB}  and  scene  topics,  then  after 13 issues, the mag was
closed,  other mags like @{B}Digital Fanzine@{UB} or @{B}LLFB's Docs@{UB} were born, but nowadays,
after some projects, the magazines are @{B}Trashcan@{UB} a scene related Mag, @{B}Revolution,
the  Mag@{UB},  @{B}LLFB's  Docs@{UB} and the AmigaGuide based @{B}AmigaChannel@{UB} which appear every
two months, covering latest news, tutorial, games, articles... 100% @{B}Amiga@{UB}!.

The  most  recent  Amiga  e-zines  are  this  one  which  you  are  reading now,
@{B}AmiChannelNews@{UB} and the forthcoming @{B}Revolution, The Mag CD-edition@{UB}!

The  next  printed  magazine is a project which seems very interesting, in a few
months we hope to be able to read it.

The  only  @{B}Amiga@{UB} related book in Spanish appeared some years ago, it's title @{B}El
Libro  del  Usuario  de  Amiga@{UB}  (@{B}The  Amiga  User's Book@{UB}) this book give you an
introduction  to the @{B}Amiga@{UB} environment and provides some tools and help to start
programming  the  @{B}Amiga@{UB} using @{B}Assembler@{UB}, excellent stuff, a must for every @{B}Amiga@{UB}
programmers.

Spain has been a good place to organize parties and little shows with the @{B}Amiga@{UB},
never a big show like @{B}WOA@{UB} or other show has been done here, only parties, but no
official presence at all.

We  hope to change this, with the forthcoming, @{B}Radykal Amiga Party@{UB} which will be
the  biggest @{B}Amiga@{UB} show in Spain ever, featuring conferences, competitions and a
lot of @{B}Amigas@{UB} everywhere!.

The lack of information in Spanish has been always a problem to newcomers to the
@{B}Amiga@{UB}, and it is difficult to get proper books.

The  release  of  @{B}Developer  CD  1.1@{UB}  helped  some  users,  but others feel very
difficult  to  start @{B}Amiga@{UB} programming in @{B}C or @{B}ASM@{UB}, that why low level languages
like @{B}Blitz Basic@{UB} or mainly @{B}Amos@{UB}, are very popular here. :-(

Some  people  had  the  clever  idea  to create a @{B}Coders Club@{UB} as the one held by
@{B}Revolution  the  Mag@{UB}  but  the main problem is the language and lack of official
help by @{B}Amiga. Int.@{UB}

But  not  everything  is  bad  in  Spain,  there  are great programmers and some
demo-scene  groups  like  @{B}Capsule@{UB},  @{B}Network@{UB},  @{B}Goblins@{UB}, @{B}AmigaCircle@{UB} or the recent
@{B}Dream's  Day@{UB}  but  the  most notable software creators are the people behind the
great  Award  Winning  WYSIWYG HTML editor @{B}Metal Web@{UB} which newer version is 2.0.
Congratulation!

There  are  people  working  with @{B}Amiga@{UB} doing arcade machines based in @{B}Amiga@{UB} and
even  development  for  Virtual Reality projects, but rarely their works and the
@{B}Amiga@{UB} name are known on the mass media.

In  my  opinion,  apart  from the usual personal use, the @{B}Amiga@{UB} is used in Spain
mainly  for  graphic  works:  video  editing, local TV stations, titles, graphic
design for webs, videogames or logos, etc.

The  little  support  given by non @{B}Amiga@{UB} medias, has killed the former users who
bought  a  @{B}A500@{UB}  and did not know how to upgrade their machines or even does not
know that @{B}Commodore@{UB} did machines like the @{B}A4000@{UB} and @{B}A1200@{UB}!.

The  most  active  users  in  Spain  as  in many countries, are connected to the
Internet  and  join some clubs like @{B}CUAE@{UB}, @{B}ACM@{UB} or @{B}SAUG@{UB}, thanks to these users and
their web sites and internal publication, users that do not have Internet can be
informed instantly.

The  basic  processor that almost every @{B}Amiga@{UB} user has is a @{B}030@{UB} 50mhz, been very
popular  the  @{B}Blizzard@{UB} series, but also there is a big number of users that have
@{B}68060  Amigas@{UB}  or even @{B}PowerPC@{UB}, now the @{B}PowerPC@{UB} fever is here, despite the @{B}Amiga
Inc.@{UB} announcement, the @{B}PowerPC@{UB} are selling very well, and everybody wants to get
a @{B}PowerPC@{UB}.

Now  with  the new @{B}Amiga@{UB} reborn, a lot of medias are looking at the @{B}Amiga@{UB} again,
we all hope to see the @{B}Amiga@{UB} again where it should be, and all the Spanish @{B}Amiga@{UB}
users will be here waiting to see it!

@{B}Amiga@{UB} Rulez!

===============================================================================
